# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1902-st-louis-browns-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The **1901 major league baseball season** was contested from April 18 through October 6, 1901.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] It was the inaugural major league season for the American League (AL) (having previously been the minor league Western League), with the Chicago White Stockings winning the AL pennant.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] In the National League (NL), in operation since 1876, the Pittsburgh Pirates won the NL pennant.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This was the first season of the modern era.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This would be the only season in which the Milwaukee Brewers played, as the team would relocate to St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis, Missouri for the following season as the St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Browns (before that team relocated to Baltimore, Maryland as the modern Baltimore Orioles in 1954, where they remain to this day.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Baltimore Orioles of this season would fold following the 1902 season).
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The 1901 schedule consisted of 140 games for all teams in the American League and National League, each of which had eight teams.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams of their respective league.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] National League Opening Day took place on April 18 with a game between the Brooklyn Superbas and the Philadelphia Phillies, while American League Opening Day did not take place until April 24, with a game between the Chicago White Stockings and the Cleveland Bluebirds.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The American League would see its final day of the season on September 28, while the National League would see its final day of the season on October 6.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] On February 27, 1901, the National League Rules Committee announced several rule changes, effective immediately.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Blue laws restricted Sunday activities in several localities, causing several teams to play at ballparks in a different locality.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games (8 in AL, 7 in NL), which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] The Cincinnati Reds would play their final game at League Park, on October 6 during a doubleheader against the St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-major-league-baseball-season] Louis Cardinals, moving into the Palace of the Fans for the start of the 1902 season.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The **1901 Milwaukee Brewers** were an American professional baseball team.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] This was the final season of the Milwaukee Brewers team that operated from 1894 to 1901, one of multiple teams in Milwaukee's professional baseball history to use the Brewers nickname, and the only season the team competed at the major-league level.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Brewers finished eighth in the inaugural season of the American League with a record of 48 wins and 89 losses, 35+1⁄2 games behind the Chicago White Stockings.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] After the season, the major-league franchise relocated and became the St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] Louis Browns, where they remained through the 1953 season, after which the franchise again relocated and became the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] A franchise in the minor-league American Association played in Milwaukee from 1902 through 1952 using the Milwaukee Brewers name.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] 4/25/01: In the first game of the season in Detroit, the Brewers held a 13–4 lead going into the ninth inning.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1901-milwaukee-brewers-season] The Detroit Tigers scored 10 runs in the bottom of the inning to win, a record which still stands as the greatest ninth inning comeback in major league baseball history.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1902 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 8th place in the American League (AL) with a record of 50–88.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and Wilbert Robinson.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team played at Oriole Park in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the season, Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the National League's (NL) New York Giants, with the financial backing of John T.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the NL's Cincinnati Reds, purchased the Orioles from John Mahon, who was deeply in debt.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] They raided the Orioles roster, releasing several of Baltimore's better players so that they could sign them to the Giants and Reds.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] AL president Ban Johnson seized control of the Orioles the next day and restocked their roster with players received on loan from other AL teams.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles' second season in Baltimore would ultimately prove to be their last, as after the season the team was replaced by the New York Highlanders, now known as the New York Yankees.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Knowing that placing a franchise in New York City was key to the success of the American League (AL), AL president Ban Johnson secretly met with principal owner John Mahon and player-manager John McGraw, who was also a part-owner, before the season about relocating to New York.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] However, the transfer did not occur when they could not find a suitable venue for the team.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In March, Mike Donlin went on a drinking binge in Baltimore, during which he was arrested for urinating in public and assaulting two chorus girls.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles released Donlin when he was sentenced to six months in prison.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Notable players jumped to the Orioles from the rival National League (NL).
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In December 1901, Joe Kelley jumped from the Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Later in the offseason, Jimmy Sheckard also jumped from Brooklyn.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kip Selbach and Jim Jackson jumped from the New York Giants, Ernie Courtney jumped from the Boston Beaneaters, Tom Hughes jumped from the Chicago Orphans, and Dan McGann jumped from the St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles signed Bill Keister as a free agent.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With these transactions, the Orioles were seen as a contender in the AL pennant going into the 1902 season.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles drew over 10,000 fans on Opening Day.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Three players returned to the NL in April 1902.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Jack Dunn and Steve Brodie jumped to the Giants in April.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sheckard changed his mind about playing for the Orioles after four games, returning to Brooklyn.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Many Orioles found themselves suspended by Johnson by midseason, including McGraw and Kelley.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In early July, McGraw resigned from the team and signed with the New York Giants of the NL.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] At this point, the Orioles had a 26–31 record.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley and Wilbert Robinson succeeded McGraw as player-managers.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The franchise began to fall into significant debt by July.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley, son-in-law of part-owner John Mahon, reported that the team owed as much as $12,000 ($446,538 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Unable to afford that debt, Mahon purchased shares of the team from Kelley and McGraw.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With this, Mahon became the majority shareholder, owning 201 of the team's 400 shares.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On July 17, 1902, Mahon sold his interest in the Orioles to Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the Giants, and John T.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the Cincinnati Reds, also of the NL.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The transaction was reported to have been in the range of $20,000 ($744,231 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] That day, Freedman and Brush released Kelley, Joe McGinnity, Roger Bresnahan, Jack Cronin, Cy Seymour, and Dan McGann from their Oriole contracts.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush then signed Kelley and Seymour to the Reds, while Freedman signed McGinnity, Bresnahan, Cronin, and McGann, joining McGraw, his new player-manager, on the Giants.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Though Kip Selbach and Jimmy Williams were both pressed to agree to relocate as well, they refused to leave Baltimore, saying they would honor their two-year contracts.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity allegedly attempted to contact Johnson that night, offering to stay with the Orioles if he could receive Johnson's personal assurance that he was welcome to stay.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity did not hear back from Johnson, who had left his phone off the hook that night to avoid being contacted, and joined his teammates with the Giants.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On that day, the Orioles were forced to forfeit their game against the St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns, as Baltimore lacked the minimum number of players required to compete.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Johnson used a league rule to join the Orioles' minority owners to seize control of the team.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Now running the Orioles, Johnson sought to restock the team.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] He requested players from the other AL franchises to fill the Orioles' roster.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sport McAllister was loaned to the Orioles from the Detroit Tigers for three games, but the Tigers requested McAllister back, as the Orioles came to Detroit to play the Tigers.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles received Pop Dillon from the Tigers, but released him after using him in two games.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Snake Wiltse was sent to the Orioles from the Philadelphia Athletics on July 19, but he struggled for the Orioles.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles also received Lew Drill on loan from the Washington Senators, sold Charlie Shields to the St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns and purchased Jack Thoney from the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles finished the season with a 50–88 record, good for last place in the AL.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] For their final game at Oriole Park, the team drew only 138 fans.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the owners meetings in late 1902, the franchise was transferred to New York.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] MLB would not return to Baltimore until the former Browns moved to Baltimore in 1954.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The **1902 Boston Americans season** was the second season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished third in the American League (AL) with a record of 77 wins and 60 losses, 6+1⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans bolstered their pitching by recruiting Bill Dinneen, who jumped from the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Dinneen and Cy Young would become the "one-two" pitching combination for the Boston Americans.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Augusta, Georgia.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 11 home runs and had 121 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .342 batting average.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 45 appearances (43 starts) and pitched 41 complete games with a 32–11 record and 2.15 ERA, while striking out 160 in 384+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team had one game end in a tie; August 18 vs.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1902 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 32nd season of the franchise.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1902 Brooklyn Superbas** finished in a distant second place in the National League, 27.5 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-chicago-orphans-season] The **1902 Chicago Orphans season** was the 31st season of the Chicago Orphans franchise, the 27th in the National League (NL), and the tenth at West Side Park.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-chicago-orphans-season] The Orphans finished fifth in the National League with a record of 68–69–6 (.496 winning percentage).
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns season** was the first for the franchise in St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The team finished second in the American League with a record of 78 wins and 58 losses.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The Milwaukee Brewers of the American League decided to relocate to St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Ownership chose the name "Browns" on purpose, as the St.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] Louis Browns had won American Association titles from 1885 to 1889.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] That team moved to the National League in 1892, became the Perfectos in 1899, and has been known as the Cardinals since 1900.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] The new Browns quickly tried to align itself with fans by raiding the rival Cardinals.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] A couple of Cardinals players were signed, including slick fielding future Hall of Fame shortstop Bobby Wallace and 1901 National League batting champion outfielder Jesse Burkett.
[src:1902-st-louis-browns-season/1902-st-louis-browns-season] While playing as the 1901 Brewers, the team had a record of 48–89 (.350) and finished in eighth place, while the 1902 Browns played to a record of 78–58 (.574) and finished in second place.
